      "pharmacodynamics": [
        "12.2 Pharmacodynamics The exposure-response relationship and time-course of pharmacodynamic response for the safety and effectiveness of AKEEGA have not been fully characterized. Hypertension and Cardiovascular Effects Niraparib has the potential to cause effects on pulse rate and blood pressure in patients, which may be related to pharmacological inhibition of the dopamine transporter (DAT), norepinephrine transporter (NET), and serotonin transporter (SERT) [see Nonclinical Toxicology (13.2) ] . Niraparib increased mean pulse rate by 22.4 to 24.1 beats/min, mean systolic blood pressure by 24.5 mmHg, and mean diastolic pressure by 16.5 mmHg relative to 14.0 to 15.8 beats per min, 18.3 to 19.6 mmHg, and 11.6 mmHg in the placebo arm. Cardiac Electrophysiology No large (>20 ms) increases in the mean QTc interval were detected following the treatment of niraparib 300 mg once daily or 1,000 mg of abiraterone acetate once daily."
